<li>Moreover , FliZ activates HilD that leads to the stimulation of SPI-1 gene expression ( Chubiz et al. , 2010 ; Hung et al. , 2012 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27404739" target="_blank">27404739</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcription of flagellar class 2 genes is positively regulated by FliZ , via the repression of YdiV , an anti-FlhD4C2 factor ( Kutsukake et al. , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27404739" target="_blank">27404739</a>]<br></li>
<li>Posttranscriptional activation of flhDC occurs at the level of the flagellar regulator FliZ via regulation of HilD activity and repression of the antiFlhD4C2 factor YdiV ( Chubiz et al. , 2010 ; Wada et al. , 2011 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27206164" target="_blank">27206164</a>]<br></li>
<li>A subset of SPI1 regulators enters the circuit via FliZ , including FlhD4C2 , required for the activation of FliZ , and RcsCDB , which represses ﬂhDC expression ( Lin et al. 2008 ; Chubiz et al. 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ is needed for eficient induction of the Spi-1 system via post-translational activation of the Spi-1 regulatory protein HilD , which in turn activates ﬂhDC gene transcription ( Iyoda et al. , 2001 ; Chubiz et al. , 2010 ; Mouslim and Hughes , 2014 ; Singer et al. , 2014 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26441883" target="_blank">26441883</a>]<br></li>
<li>Primary examples of factors that inﬂuence HilD activity are HilE , a major negative regulator of SPI1 T3SS expression , and the ﬂagellar gene product FliZ , which acts indirectly upon HilD to increase activity ( 10 , 16 , 18 -- 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29378886" target="_blank">29378886</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , while both HilE and FliZ act through HilD , the effects of FliZ are the same in wild-type and hilE backgrounds , indicating that these two factors regulate HilD independently of each other .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>HilE and FliZ regulate the activity of HilD simultaneously and independently ( 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29378886" target="_blank">29378886</a>]<br></li>
<li>Presumably , these changes are due to the secretion-dependent regulation of FlhD4C2 activity by FliT and FliZ ( Yamamoto and Kutsukake , 2006 ; Saini et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21166907" target="_blank">21166907</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliA autoregulation and activation of FliZ , and FliZ-dependent positive regulation of FlhD4C2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , control of class I proteins by FliZ is reported to be predominantly post-translational ( Saini et al. , 2008 ) , and availability of cellular factors impacting translation , activation , and stability of FlhD4C2 may also fluctuate with growth-phase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>This boost in virulence was suggested to be caused by increased flagellar expression , including the FliZ regulator controlling the SPI1 regulator HilD at post-transcriptional level ( Kage et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23676436" target="_blank">23676436</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with the notion that FliZ activates T3SS-1 expression through HilD , transcription of hilD was induced in a tviA defective strain ( Fig. 1A , cluster 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19703107" target="_blank">19703107</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taking all of our data into account , we hypothesize that FliZ controls-the-activity of HilD by direct interaction , but we can not currently rule out indirect effects .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ negatively regulates transcription of the ydiV gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>We tested whether the absence of FliZ caused increased levels of RpoS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22356617" target="_blank">22356617</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , the presence of a hilD mutation blocked FliZ induction of hilA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , although the half-life of HilD is slightly affected by changes in FliZ levels , this does not explain the mechanism of regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>The stability of HilD protein is affected slightly by the presence or absence of FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this work , we further characterize the mechanism of FliZ regulation of HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the basis of this experiment , they implied that FliZ regulates HilD at the level of translation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , in Xenorhabdus nematophila , FliZ activates transcription of class II ﬂagellar genes by binding directly to the ﬂhDC promoter ( 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that the enhanced FliZ level in the ﬂgM mutant does not lead to upregulation of FliA production , which conforms to our observation in Fig. 2A .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vivo data suggest that during infection , FliZ acts to overcome the negative regulation of HilE to switch on SPI1 T3SS expression in the intestine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29378886" target="_blank">29378886</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data suggest that FliZ plays a major role in the regulation of SPI1 in response to periplasmic disulﬁde bond status .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like the FliZ control , the ﬂa-gellar and invasion systems are both regulated in the same manner by these effectors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11162188" target="_blank">11162188</a>]<br></li>
<li>While FliZ controls FlhD4C2 amounts in the cell , FliT controls-the-activity of the FlhD4C2 transcription factor complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ activates the class 2 ﬂagellar genes only in the presence of the ﬂa-gellar activator proteins , FlhD/FlhC [ 16 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11162188" target="_blank">11162188</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that , in the presence of FliZ , the enzyme activity was much lower in the ydiV mutant than in the wildtype strain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , overproduction of FliZ no longer activated hilA in the hilD background .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , hilA expression in this background was even more signiﬁcantly affected by FliZ than in the wild type ; activity was decreased about 20-fold in the absence of FliZ and increased 3-fold when FliZ was overexpressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the absence of FliZ , hilA expression was reduced only 2-fold in the dsbA mutant or dsbA srgA double mutant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of aTc , TetR negatively regulates the PLtetO-1 promoter and , as a consequence , FliZ or FliA is weakly expressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the presence of aTc , TetR no longer represses the PLtetO-1 promoter and FliZ or FliA is strongly expressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , we show that the previously described ability of 28 to activate Pclass2/middle gene expression is , in fact , due to FliZ , as both are expressed from the same overlapping Pclass2 and Pclass3 promoters at the ﬂiAZY locus .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , RtsB has been reported not to directly act on the SPI-1 genes , and this effect mirrors that observed in the absence of FliZ ( 15 , 231 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
<li>HilD also controls the flagella regulon ( FliZ ) ( 3 ) , implying that the motility decrease in STP22 ~ and STP22 + treated with CEOs can be attributed to the repression of hiID .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24780330" target="_blank">24780330</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although the data in Fig. 4 suggest that RcsCDB and FliZ independently affect SPI1 expression in the dsbA mutant , this interpretation is complicated by the fact that RcsB and cofactor RcsA can negatively regulate the ﬂagellar regulon ( including FliZ ) by binding directly to the ﬂhDC promoter region ( 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , our results suggest that the increased hilA expression seen in the absence of Lon is not due to increased stability of HilD but to increased stability of FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>The FliZ regulator is known to enhance activity of the HilD protein ( 41 ) through an unknown posttranslational step ; therefore , the inﬂuence of overexpression of FliZ on hilA-lacZ in response to temperature was tested .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26386070" target="_blank">26386070</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the absence of FlhD4C2 autoregulation , the decrease is due solely to FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>( A ) FliZ is unable to regulate PﬁmA promoter activity in the absence of FimZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20833811" target="_blank">20833811</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , FliZ appears to be stabilized in the absence of Lon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>The absence of FliZ leads to a fall in the intracellular levels of FlhD4C2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the results from X. nematophila regarding FliZ being a DNA-binding protein , the most likely mechanism in S. enterica serovar Typhimurium is that FliZ increases the expression of some protein that stabilizes FlhD4C2 or , alternatively , inhibits the expression of a protease such as ClpXP that degrades it .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the impact of FliZ upon the fliC census is enhanced at 5 hours compared to 2.5 hours under conditions of metered expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>In conjunction with FliZ , RcsCDB could be the intermediate in the SPI1 response to a variety of environmental conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to test this , gel mobility shift assay of the 32P-labeled DNA fragment containing PnlpC was performed in the presence of the puriﬁed His6-FliZ protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 2A , the intracellular level of FliZ increased in the ﬂgM mutant , probably owing to the increased level of P2 transcript .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , activation of the hilA gene by FliZ occurs even in the absence of FlhD/FlhC [ 13 , our unpublished results ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11162188" target="_blank">11162188</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of FliZ , the rate of decrease in class 2 gene expression ( with increasing starvation ) is much more rapid as compared to wild type .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>We characterized the effect of loss of a given SPI1 regulator on hilA expression in otherwise wild-type , ﬂiZ null , and hilD null backgrounds , as well as in a strain in which FliZ is expressed under the control of the tetRA promoter , and thus independently of FlhD4C2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li>
<li>The absence of FliZ is `` sensed '' by the cell in terms of reduced HBB expression , and the cell tried to compensate for this loss of HBB expression by retaining more of FlhD4C2 in the cell in its free form .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>This result and the fact that the increase in hilA expression seen in the lon mutant i dependent on FliZ suggest that the primary consequence of losing Lon is increased stability of FliZ , which in turn activates HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>To examine whether FliZ is involved in the posttranscriptional control of HilD , we decided to compare the levels of HilD protein in ﬂiZ and ﬂiZ cells where hilD is expressed under the regulation of the PA1lacO-1 promoter system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Coordinated regulation of the ﬂagellar regulon and SPI-1 in a FliZ-dependent manner was also demonstrated to be regulated by the ClpXP protease , affecting the turnover of the FlhD4C2 complex , FlhD4C2 in turn controls FliZ expression , which regulates the cellular levels of HilD ( 50 , 51 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26056383" target="_blank">26056383</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , the increased transcription of hilC and hilD in the clpPX cells could be explained by ampliﬁcation of the regulatory loop in which FliZ triggered an increase in the amount of HilD via posttranscriptional control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , in a rich nutritional environment where the amount of the YdiV protein is low , the FlhD4C2 complex is free from inhibition by YdiV , resulting in high expression of the FliZ protein , which in turn represses ydiV expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is apparently inconsistent with the above-mentioned observation that the intracellular level of FliZ was increased by the ﬂgM mutation , because the FliZ protein expressed should increase the P1 transcript of the ﬂiAZ operon and thus enhance FliA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ , which is encoded by the ﬂiAZY operon of the ﬂagellar regulon , activates the expression of hilD at the posttranscriptional level , leading to the stimulation of SPI1 gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ Acts as a Repressor of the ydiV Gene , Which Encodes an Anti-FlhD4C2 Factor of the Flagellar Regulon in Salmonella enterica Serovar Typhimurium Takeo Wada , Yasushi Tanabe , and Kazuhiro Kutsukake * Graduate School of Natural Science and Technology and Department of Biology , Faculty of Science , Okayama University , Tsushima-Naka 3-1-1 , Kita-ku , Okayama 700-8530 , Japan Received 2 June 2011/Accepted 19 July 2011 YdiV acts as an anti-FlhD4C2 factor , which negatively regulates the class 2 ﬂagellar operons in poor medium in Salmonella enterica serovar Typhimurium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , our results suggest that the previously observed effect of 28 on Pclass2 activity was actually via FliZ , for as FliZ is under the control of both Pclass2 and P 28 class3 promoters , overexpressing increases FliZ expression , which thus leads to increased Pclass2 activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>Increased FliZ expression then leads to increased stability of FlhD4C2 and , as a consequence , further activation of the Pclass2 promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ and YdiV participate in a genetic circuit of mutually repressing repressors ( figure 1 ) , wherein FliZ repression of ydiV is predicted to increase flagellar class II gene expression because YdiV inhibits binding of the FlhD4C2 complex to DNA and targets the complex for ClpXP-mediated proteolysis ( Takaya et al. , 2012 , Wada et al. , 2011a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>The FlhD2C2 complex activates transcription of the ﬂiAZY operon , and the s28 ( FliA ) and FliZ protein products act to increase ﬂagellar gene expression : s28 will transcribe early , middle , and late genes , and FliZ enhances the function of the FlhD2C2 complex on class 2 promoter transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11104815" target="_blank">11104815</a>]<br></li>
<li>Repression and activation by YdiV and FliZ ( respectively ) can shape the census of fliC expression independently , and bistability collapses into a predominantly intermediate population in the absence of both regulators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Immobilized growth prevented the induction of SPI1 , SPI4 and SPI5 gene expression , likely mediated by the FliZ transcriptional-regulator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22356617" target="_blank">22356617</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , FlhDC induces the expression of FliZ that somehow increases activity of HilD and thus the expression of the SPI-1 genes36 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27886269" target="_blank">27886269</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the phenotypes we observed were not consistent with the expected effect of increased FliZ levels , being increased expression of hilD and virulence expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23676436" target="_blank">23676436</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , reduced levels of FliZ are expected to lead to reduced levels of the transcriptional-regulators HilA ( controlled by HilD ) and InvF ( controlled by HilA ) , both of which are known to activate the expression of effector genes located inside and outside ( indicated by a dotted box ) SPI-1 ( 77 -- 79 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29150501" target="_blank">29150501</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the population level , this suggests temporal fluctuations in average concentrations of cellular factors required for FliZ to activate fliC expression , most likely regulators of class I. Transcription of class I genes is tightly controlled by growth-phase specific expression of multiple positive and negative regulators ( Mouslim & Hughes , 2014 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>If this were the sole mechanism by which FliZ increased FlhC , the amount of FlhC should be identical between ΔydiV and ΔydiV ΔfliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Analysis of this model demonstrated that , in principle , the two feedback loops controlled by FliZ and YdiV are sufﬁcient for bistability .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161191" target="_blank">25161191</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taking these results together , it is suggested that SPI1 expression is regulated by ClpXP through a mechanism by which FliZ controls the cellular levels of the transcriptional-regulators HilC and HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results show that disruption of ﬂiZ signiﬁcantly decreased the cellular level of HilD even when the corresponding gene was expressed by the PA1lacO-1 promoter system , suggesting that HilD is controlled posttranscriptionally by FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Subsequent experiments showed that the enhancement of cellular levels of HilC and HilD by clpPX disruption seemed to be caused by an increase in the ﬂagellar protein FliZ , encoded by the class 2 ﬂiAZY operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , with increase in starvation level , the signiﬁcance of FliZ in maintaining population level HBB distribution increases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29473025" target="_blank">29473025</a>]<br></li>
<li>Intriguingly , though fliZ was induced throughout the population ( figure S5 ) in our metered strain , the ability of FliZ to counter YdiV-dependent ( figure 5B , panels 11,12,17,18 ) and -- independent ( figure 5B , panels 10,16 ) fliC repression varies from cell to cell .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in contrast to observations at 2.5 hours , metered induction of FliZ now partitioned cells into fliC-HIGH in the presence and absence of YdiV ( figure 5B , compare fliC-HIGH subpopulations in panels 4 -- 6 , where FliZ is not induced , to fliC-HIGH subpopulations in panels 10 -- 12 and 16 -- 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>A shifted band was observed in the presence of His6-FliZ , and its amount increased in a concentration-dependent manner ( Fig. 4 , lanes 2 to 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>A β-galactosidase reporter fusion was used to measure ydiV transcription in the presence and absence of FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Cells low in activated FlhD4C2 would require more FliZ to activate fliC expression , and cells with higher concentrations of activated FlhD4C2 would require more YdiV to switch off fliC expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>The instability of FliZ has made it difﬁcult to provide biochemical data to prove or disprove direct interaction , and conﬁrmation of our hypothesis requires further investigation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previous work showed FimY acts upstream of FimZ to activate the ﬁm operon , while FliZ functions to repress FimZ posttranscriptionally ( 34 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28439039" target="_blank">28439039</a>]<br></li>
<li>Prior to completion of the HBB , FlhD4C2 can only partially activate Pclass2 promoters due to low protein levels arising from weak FliZ expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>In other words , this mechanism would enable cells to increase gene expression when there are too few ﬂagella , due to the action of FliZ at low secretion rates , and decrease gene expression when there are too many , due to the action of FliT at high secretion rates .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>One potential mechanism from this hypothesis is that FliZ binds to FliT and prevents it from inhibiting FlhD4C2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ activation is dependent upon FlhD4C2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>We next examined HilD protein levels in response to FliZ - or HilE-mediated regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>Whether FliZ 's role in flagellar regulation contributes to infection is unknown .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>One possibility is that FliZ regulates ﬂhDC transcription , resulting in an indirect effect on Pclass2 activity due to changes in FlhD4C2 expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>To date , in Salmonella , FliZ is known to independently regulate three very different transcriptional-regulators , HilD , RpoS , and FlhD4C2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>One possibility is that FliZ posttranscriptionally regulates FimZ in a manner similar to FlhD4C2 and HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20833811" target="_blank">20833811</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ , whose function is also not well understood , appears to induce hilA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>This increase seems to be dependent on FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , we found that the positive feedback loop involving FliA is required , although its role appears to be solely to enhance FliZ expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161191" target="_blank">25161191</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , these two indirect effects are assumed to be mediated by FliZ ; RtsB represses FliZ , which has been shown to activate SPI-1 expression but repress type I ﬁmbriae .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">FliZ protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>RpoE Affects Transcriptional Expression of ﬂiA and ﬂjB : z66 But Not ﬂhD at 30 and 120 min Under Hyperosmotic Stress Table 3 Flagellar genes with gene expression changes in mutant DrpoE Hierarchy Description of gene product Name log2 ( DrpoE/WT ) Class-1 ﬂhDC Flagellar-transcriptional-activator Transcriptional activator FlhD ﬂhC ﬂhD -0.21 0.64 Class-2 ﬂgAMN Flagellar basal body P-ring biosynthesis protein Negative regulator of ﬂagellin synthesis Flagella synthesis protein FlgN ﬂgA ﬂgM ﬂgN ﬂgB ﬂgC ﬂgD ﬂgE ﬂgF ﬂgG ﬂgH ﬂgI ﬂgJ N -1.37 -1.25 ﬂgBCDEFGHIJKL Flagellar basal body rod protein Flagellar basal body rod protein -0.68 N -0.81 Flagellar basal body rod modiﬁcation protein Flagellar hook protein -0.84 N N Putative ﬂagellar basal-body rod protein FlgF Flagellar basal-body rod protein FlgG Flagellar-L-ring-protein precursor Flagellar-P-ring-protein precursor Flagellar biosynthesis protein N N N Flagellar hook-associated protein Flagellar hook-associated protein Flagellar biosynthesis protein ﬂgK ﬂgL ﬂhB ﬂhA ﬂhE ﬂiA ﬂiZ ﬂiY ﬂiD ﬂiS ﬂiT ﬂiE -1.65 -1.46 N N ﬂhBAE Flagellar biosynthesis protein Flagellar-protein-FlhE precursor Flagellar biosynthesis sigma factor FliA N ﬂiAZY -2.03 -0.49 FliZ protein Cystine-binding periplasmic protein precursor Flagellar hook-associated protein -1.08 -1.31 -0.48 ﬂiDST Flagellar-protein-FliS Flagellar-protein-FliT N N ﬂiE Flagellar basal body protein ﬂiFGHIJK Flagellar M-ring protein Flagellar motor protein Flagellar assembly protein ﬂiF ﬂiG ﬂiH ﬂiI ﬂiJ ﬂiK ﬂiL ﬂiM ﬂiN ﬂiO ﬂiP -0.28 N N Flagellum-speciﬁc ATP synthase Flagellar protein Flagellar hook-length control protein N N N ﬂiLMNOPQR N N Flagellar biosynthesis protein Flagellar motor switch protein Flagellar motor switch protein 0.29 N N Flagellar protein FliO Flagellar biosynthesis protein Flagellar biosynthesis protein N ﬂiQ ﬂiR Flagellar biosynthesis protein 0.41 Class-3 ﬂjBA ﬂjB ﬂjA -2.86 N -1.46 Phase-2 ﬂagellin protein Phase-1 ﬂagellin repressor ﬂgM ﬂgN ﬂgK ﬂgL ﬂgMN Negative regulator of ﬂagellin synthesis -1.15 -1.65 -1.46 Flagella synthesis protein FlgN Flagellar hook-associated protein Flagellar hook-associated protein ﬂgKL The expression of ﬂagella-related genes is affected by environmental factors , such as osmotic [ 23 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20717675" target="_blank">20717675</a>]<br></li>
<li>The instability of FliZ has made it difﬁcult to provide biochemical data to prove or disprove direct interaction , and conﬁrmation of our hypothesis requires further investigation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>It seems unlikely that FliZ itself acts as a transcriptional regulator , since it contains no apparent DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10714991" target="_blank">10714991</a>]<br></li>
<li>From this , we note that the two feedback loops in the network ( FliZ - and FliT-dependent ) likely serve two distinct purposes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>The function of FliZ is unknown , and its predicted product shows no signiﬁcant homology to any known protein or structural motif .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of this domain suggests that FliZ is a DNA-binding protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>Kutsukake et al. ( 68 ) pointed out that FliZ protein is predicted to contain a coiled-coil domain , which is believed to be involved in protein-protein interactions ( 83 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11104815" target="_blank">11104815</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal portion of FliZ contains a SAM-like phage integrase domain ( 37 ) , which is also included in Cre , Flp , and XerD recombinases ( 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , interestingly , a search of the `` conserved domains '' database shows that the C-terminal half of FliZ has a sterile alpha motif ( SAM ) - like fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>Despite its apparent posttranslational effects in Salmonella and E. coli , the FliZ protein contains a region that resembles the core DNA-binding domain of phage integrases ( 49 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , such promiscuity in FliZ DNA-binding between the organisms is not altogether unreasonable , as the greatest difference between the two FliZ orthologs is at the C terminus , the region predicted to bind DNA based on the homology to the SAM-like phage integrase domain ( 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ is known to contain a SAM ( sterile alpha motif ) - like phage integrase domain ( 37 ) , suggesting the possibility that FliZ has a DNA-binding ability .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">FliZ evolution</font></label>
