<li>FliZ induces a kinetic switch in ﬂagellar gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29473025" target="_blank">29473025</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23873910" target="_blank">23873910</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24488311" target="_blank">24488311</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161191" target="_blank">25161191</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>FliZ , whose function is also not well understood , appears to induce hilA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , FliA positively regulates its own expression , as well as that of the genes encoding FlgM , FliZ , FliD , and FliT ( Gillen and Hughes , 1993 ; Kutsukake and Ide , 1995 ; Ikebe et al. , 1999a , b ; Kutsukake et al. , 1999 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29473025" target="_blank">29473025</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliA and FliZ are expressed from a single operon , and are activated independently by FlhD4C2 and FliA ( Kutsukake et al. , 1999 ; Brown et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29473025" target="_blank">29473025</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ was put under control of its native promoter by cloning the ﬂiAZ operon with its promoter using primers SS123F ( GGG CTC GAG AGT TTT CGC GCC CAA ATA CC ) and SS123R ( AAT AAG CTT TTA ATA TAT ATC AGA ACT GG ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note 4 2 that FliZ is indirectly regulated by late protein secretion , as its expression is controlled by 28 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>The inability to activate SPI-1 expression by growth at 42 ° C is overcome by overexpression of RtsA or HilC but not by overexpression of FliZ or HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26386070" target="_blank">26386070</a>]<br></li>
<li>BarA/SirA ( 1 ) , HilD ( 14 , 30 ) , HilC/SirC/SprA ( 11 , 12 , 28 , 30 ) , CsrAB ( 1 ) , PhoB , FadD , and FliZ ( 25 ) have been shown to activate hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16391141" target="_blank">16391141</a>]<br></li>
<li>The other mutations have no effect on hilD expression , suggesting that FadD , FliZ , and EnvZ do not regulate hilA by modulating hilD expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have also shown that FadD , FliZ , and EnvZ do not regulate hilA expression by modulating hilD expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results suggest that FliZ , FadD , PhoB , EnvZ , and SirA each affect hilA expression independently and act through distinct pathways .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10714991" target="_blank">10714991</a>]<br></li>
<li>Previously , we provided evidence that FadD , FliZ , PhoB , SirA , and EnvZ regulate hilA expression by independent pathways ( 48 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ and RcsBC affect hilA expression through HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ regulates hilA independently of HilE and RpoS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 7 HilE and FliZ affect hilA expression independently of each other .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li>
<li>Complementation studies with ﬂhC and ﬂiA mutants indicate that FliZ , which is encoded in an operon with ﬂiA , activates expression of hilA , linking regulation of hilA with motility .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10714991" target="_blank">10714991</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , hilC is not required for the regulation of hilA expression by oxygen , osmolarity , FadD , FliZ , PhoB , or SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="TU_collapse_similarity" for="tu_similarity_27">
Because the URS is required for regulation of hilA expression by oxygen , osmolarity , PhoP/PhoQ , and SirA/BarA ( 63 ) , we tested whether this cis element is also required for regulation of hilA expression by FadD , FliZ , PhoB , and EnvZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></label>
<input id="tu_similarity_27", type="checkbox">
<div class="TU_similar">
<li>Thus , the same regulatory node that is required for regulation of hilA expression by SirA , PhoP/PhoQ , oxygen , and osmolarity is also required by FadD , FliZ , PhoB , and EnvZ to modulate hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Thus , it appears that FadD , FliZ , PhoB , and SirA act independently of hilC to reduce hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>More recently , it was found that PhoP / PhoQ , FadD , FliZ , PhoB , SirA , and EnvZ require the URS for modulation of hilA expression , but these factors are not responsible for regulating hilA in response to oxygen and osmolarity ( 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11673432" target="_blank">11673432</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was demonstrated that FliZ posttranslationally controls HilD to positively regulate expression of hilA [ 67 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22632036" target="_blank">22632036</a>]<br></li>
<li>The possibility that Lon targets FliZ to repress hilA expression can be excluded because lon disruption does not affect the production of ﬂagellum-related proteins whose expression is activated by FliZ ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11741864" target="_blank">11741864</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , controlled expression of ﬂiZ results in high-level expression of hilA , suggesting that FliZ somehow induces hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA , OmpR , FadD , and FliZ may also modulate hilD posttranscriptionally to regulate hilA expression DISCUSSION Previously , Schechter et al. demonstrated that hilA expression is repressed in the absence of hilD ( 63 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>30:81 -- 90 , 2001 ) have shown that a disruption in ﬂiZ represses hilA , conﬁrming that FliZ positively regulates hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results are consistent with our model that FliZ is functioning through HilD to control hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="TU_collapse_similarity" for="tu_similarity_37">
These results suggest that , while TdcA regulates ﬂiZ transcription , its effect on hilA expression is independent of FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></label>
<input id="tu_similarity_37", type="checkbox">
<div class="TU_similar">
<li>However , our results suggest that while TdcA regulates ﬂiZ transcription , its effect on hilA expression is independent of FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The expressed FliZ protein activates autog-enously the transcription from the P1 promoter by repressing the anti-FlhD4C2 gene ydiV , while the expressed FliA protein ( 28 ) associates with RNA polymerase core enzyme and then transcribes the ﬂiAZ operon from the P2 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ negatively regulates transcription of the ydiV gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ represses ydiV transcription from the nlpC promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>If FliZ affects hilA expression solely through HilD , then there should be no ﬂiZ phenotype in a hilD background when the system is activated by other means .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>It should be noted that the chromosomal ydiV-lacZ fusion gene was not completely turned off by FliZ expression from pQE80L-ﬂiZ ( Table 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , it is reasonable to predict that this FliZ control may not be affected by the ydiV mutation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>lum-related gene product FliZ positively regulates hilD expression at the posttranscriptional level ( 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18723621" target="_blank">18723621</a>]<br></li>
<li>This indicates that YdiV activates its own expression by inhibiting FliZ expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ represses expression of YdiV transcriptionally .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under certain experimental conditions ( e. g. , in rich medium ) , the YdiV-FliZ repressing circuit is not required for ﬂiC bistable expression [ 74 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29369799" target="_blank">29369799</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ was required for WT levels of fliC expression , however , bistable populations continued to form in a ΔfliZ strain , indicating that reciprocal repression by YdiV and FliZ is not crucial for fliC bistability .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ boosted fliC expression only when ydiV was concurrently induced ( figure 5B , columns 2 and 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , both the kinetic pattern of ydiV repression by FliZ ( figure 3A ) and FlhC regulation by FliZ ( figure 3B ) support our fliC transcription timecourse , in which FliZ increases fliC expression at later timepoints during growth ( figure 2A-E ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ represses ydiV , and increases both class I protein levels ( figure 3B ) and fliC expression in the absence of ydiV ( figure 4A , B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under these conditions , the anti-sigma factor FlgM should not be exported and should block class III transcription ( 36 , 51 ) and decrease FliZ expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>YdiV and FliZ are necessary for bimodal ﬂagellar gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161191" target="_blank">25161191</a>]<br></li>
<li>In particular , we found that deleting FliZ decreases the relative magnitudes of ﬂagellar and SPI1 gene expression but does not affect their dynamics ( Fig. 4A and B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20833811" target="_blank">20833811</a>]<br></li>
<li>We also found that overexpressing FliZ increases both the magnitudes and durations of ﬂagellar and SPI1 gene expression ( Fig. 4D and E ) , whereas it represses and delays type 1 ﬁmbrial gene expression ( Fig. 4F ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20833811" target="_blank">20833811</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ﬂiZ gene is transcribed in the ﬂiAZ operon , and FliZ activates the Spi1 transcriptional activator HilD , which in turn activates Spi1 transcription under high salt ( 200 mM NaCl ) microaerobic growth conditions ( 48 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24706743" target="_blank">24706743</a>]<br></li>
<li>28 ( FliA ) and FliZ are encoded by the ﬂiA and ﬂiZ genes , respectively , which together constitute an operon transcribed in this order .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>]<br></li>
<li>The class 2 promoter is also under positive and negative control from FliZ and FliT , respectively , both of which are encoded by the genes within the ﬂagellar regulon ( 28 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>]<br></li>
<li>As FliZ is also a positive regulator of Pclass2 activity , this means that two positive factors are encoded in the same operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>The second mechanism by which FliZ activates Class 2 and 3 gene transcription in Salmonella is via positive feedforward regulation of invasion gene expression encoded on Spi-1 ( Lucas et al. , 2000 ; Iyoda et al. , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26441883" target="_blank">26441883</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ regulates invasion gene expression by controlling the availability of hilD , encoding an activator of hilA ( Kage et al. , 2008 , Lin et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19703107" target="_blank">19703107</a>]<br></li>
<li>Intriguingly , many cells are able to maximize fliC expression in the absence of FliZ , revealing biochemical heterogeneity in these well-mixed , homogeneously grown cultures .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>B ) FliZ 's impact upon fliC transcription remains time-dependent , and heterogeneity in fliC expression is maintained in the metered system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ control of these genes was observed in rich medium , in which YdiV expression must be low .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , FliZ was shown to be a positive regulator of class 2 operons ( 23 ) and to participate in a positive-feedback loop that induces a kinetic switch in class 2 operon expression ( 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>Recently , FliZ was shown to be a transcriptional repressor of the nonﬂagellar gene ydiV ( 46 ) , which encodes another anti-FlhD4C2 factor responsible for repression of ﬂagellar expression in poor medium ( 45 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21908664" target="_blank">21908664</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , these results indicate that the DsbA effect on hilA expression is dependent on both the RcsCDB system and FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with the notion that FliZ activates T3SS-1 expression through HilD , transcription of hilD was induced in a tviA defective strain ( Fig. 1A , cluster 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19703107" target="_blank">19703107</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data above suggest that , although loss of the ﬂagellar apparatus can affect FliZ expression , it does not explain th decrease in transcription observed in the rcsBC background when dsbA is also mutated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that the late FliZ ( expressed from class 3 ) does not have any role in control of ﬂagella gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ is expressed in the same operon as FliA , and controls class 2 gene expression via a protein YdiV ( Wada et al. 2011 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ , encoded in the ﬂiAZY operon , is a positive activator of P / class2 middle gene expression ( 37 , 48 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ is encoded in the ﬂiA operon and is reported to be an enhancer of class II ﬂagellar gene expression ( 31 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , reduced levels of FliZ are expected to lead to reduced levels of the transcriptional regulators HilA ( controlled by HilD ) and InvF ( controlled by HilA ) , both of which are known to activate the expression of effector genes located inside and outside ( indicated by a dotted box ) SPI-1 ( 77 -- 79 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29150501" target="_blank">29150501</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , there was no strict correlation between the level of HilD protein and the level of hilA expression ; HilD protein levels in the ﬂiZ and pFliZ backgrounds differed by only 2-fold , whereas hilA transcription differed by 10-fold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , FliZ is also known to activate expression of the genes located on the Salmonella Pathogenicity Island-1 ( SPI1 ) ( Chubiz et al. 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>We predicted that deleting both ydiV and fliZ would invert the WT census of fliC expression as cells approach stationary phase , since YdiV is critical to maintain the fliC-OFF subpopulation , and FliZ is required to maximize fliC expression under these conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the impact of FliZ upon the fliC census is enhanced at 5 hours compared to 2.5 hours under conditions of metered expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , the Lrp-binding consensus II motifs are linked with several genes , ﬂhC ( affects FliZ expression ) , hns , and ompR ( data not shown ) , whose products are known to be involved in the expression of hilA ( 62 , 63 , 84 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19074398" target="_blank">19074398</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the population level , this suggests temporal fluctuations in average concentrations of cellular factors required for FliZ to activate fliC expression , most likely regulators of class I. Transcription of class I genes is tightly controlled by growth-phase specific expression of multiple positive and negative regulators ( Mouslim & Hughes , 2014 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>If the regulator of interest controls hilA by affecting expression of FliZ , loss of this regulator would no longer affect hilA expression in the absence of FliZ or when FliZ was ectopically expressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , overexpression of FliZ in the ydiV strain did not attain a level of expression of PﬂiA-lacZ equivalent to its expression level in the ydiV mutant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>The absence of FliZ is `` sensed '' by the cell in terms of reduced HBB expression , and the cell tried to compensate for this loss of HBB expression by retaining more of FlhD4C2 in the cell in its free form .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25972986" target="_blank">25972986</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ﬂiZ mutation did not have a signiﬁcant effect on the sirA expression , indicating that FliZ control of the hilA expression is not mediated by transcriptional activation of the sirA gene .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11162188" target="_blank">11162188</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results in Figure S1 show that the hilD -- lac transcriptional and translational fusions were also not affected by the loss of FliZ , conﬁrming that FliZ controls hilA expression via the post-translational control of HilD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , FliZ-dependent activation of class 2 operon expression is achieved by repression of the ydiV gene by FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results indicate that FliZ is a repressor of the nlpC-ydiV operon and activates the class 2 operons by repressing ydiV expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggested the possibility that FliZ control of class 2 operon expression is exerted via the regulatory pathway of ydiV expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>These include the transcription factors FliZ , HilC , and RtsA , which have each been demonstrated to positively regulate invasion gene expression by promoting expression of the SPI-1 regulator hilD ( 9 , 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27185788" target="_blank">27185788</a>]<br></li>
<li>Rather , positive feedback is indirect , such that FliA activates FliZ expression and FliZ indirectly activates FliA expression by repressing the expression of YdiV .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161191" target="_blank">25161191</a>]<br></li>
<li>We demonstrate sustained bistable fliC expression in virulent Salmonella 14028 and document dynamic control of the distribution , or single-cell census , of flagellar gene expression by the mutually repressing repressors YdiV and FliZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both nutrients and FliZ 4 2 repress the expression of YdiV ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25161191" target="_blank">25161191</a>]<br></li>
<li>Metered expression of YdiV and FliZ reveals variable sensitivity to these regulators and defines conditions where expression of FliZ enhances fliC expression and where FliZ does not alter the fliC census .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , we conclude that the regulations of ﬂagellar gene expression by FliZ and SPI1 are independent of each other .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18469103" target="_blank">18469103</a>]<br></li>
<li>Bistability of ΔfliZ populations and ydiV-independent FliZ control of flagellar gene expression provide evidence that the YdiV-FliZ mutually repressing repressor circuit is not required for bistability .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25315056" target="_blank">25315056</a>]<br></li>
<li>Levels of hilC and hilD transcription in the absence of ClpXP and/or FliZ in cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>FlhD4C2 , via the ﬂagella regulon members FliA and FliZ positively regulates expression of the type III secretion system through hilA encoding the master activator of the TTSS genes ( Fig. 7 ; Chubiz et al. , 2010 ; Fabrega and Vila , 2013 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24127899" target="_blank">24127899</a>]<br></li>
<li>Recent studies revealed the coordinate regulation of flagellar and SPI-1 genes by FliZ , encoded by a gene in the fliA operon [ 66,67 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22632036" target="_blank">22632036</a>]<br></li>
<li>Puriﬁed FliZ protein was shown in vitro to bind to the promoter region of the nlpC gene , which is located just upstream of the ydiV gene , and to repress its transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>Models illustrating the FliZ-dependent activation of the ﬂagellar class 2 operons via control of the expression of the ydiV gene ( A ) and the interplay between YdiV and FliZ in motility control in response to nutritional conditions ( B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>Instead , we showed that FliZ binds to the promoter region of the nlpC-ydiV operon and represses its transcription ( Fig. 3 and 4 ) , which results in the decreased expression of the ydiV gene , encoding an anti-FlhD4C2 factor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21804009" target="_blank">21804009</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ is encoded by a gene in the ﬂiA operon , and orthologs are found only in the ﬂagellar regulons of members of the family Enterobacteriaceae .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20889744" target="_blank">20889744</a>]<br></li>
<li>FliZ , which is encoded by the ﬂiAZY operon of the ﬂagellar regulon , activates the expression of hilD at the posttranscriptional level , leading to the stimulation of SPI1 gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
